CA Full Time;UX Research Associate;Californie;Apply Now;"This project will help address one of the main areas of friction for addressing more user harm from Google Play apps. SDKs are a large and common vector of abuse in an app – and when the risk team detects SDKs causing harm
column3: they then work to remediate and enforce on this harm. The remediation and enforcement process includes warning app developers of the SDK issue
column5: and then removing or suspending apps that continue to be violating policies.

column1: The challenge is that the appeals team in their current process
column2: is limited by capacity to handle appeals from 4-6K app removals each month– which is a hard limitation to acting quickly and in bulk on the harm that we see. If
column5: 000 apps – we are not able to action on these at once or together in a consistent way as we are constrained in time by the appeals capacity.

column1: The hypothesis is that there are low hanging fruit wins that can be addressed in the current appeals process to unlock appeals bandwidth in the short term. There is also an opportunity to understand what other pinpoints that are can be addressed (in the longer term) with engineering (tooling) support. We are asking for a UXR resource that can work alongside the Appeals team to identify these pinpoints and suggest opportunities. This is critical for short term velocity and impact – there is no resource in the Appeals team available for this work (they are all responding to and managing appeals).
Map out the user flow of the main uses cases / problems that bring app developers to appeal (related to an SDK issue). Start from the Play developer console experience
· Root cause study of the issues (appeals are the symptoms). This includes detailed analysis upstream

o How to provide sufficient information to developers upon enforcement so that developer can self-fix the issues without coming to appeals (eg. what information is missing for dev to self-fix issues?)
o How to increase the awareness of SDK violations so that developers are aware that they are required to make fixes while they are not intentionally violating policies
o How to effectively warn developers so that they fix issues in advance to the enforcement
o How to educate developers on technical details (eg. need to roll out updated APK at 100% to deactivate non-compliant APK)

column4: 800/Year;"This project will help address one of the main areas of friction for addressing more user harm from Google Play apps. SDKs are a large and common vector of abuse in an app – and when the risk team detects SDKs causing harm
column5: they then work to remediate and enforce on this harm. The remediation and enforcement process includes warning app developers of the SDK issue
column7: and then removing or suspending apps that continue to be violating policies.

column1: The challenge is that the appeals team in their current process
column2: is limited by capacity to handle appeals from 4-6K app removals each month– which is a hard limitation to acting quickly and in bulk on the harm that we see. If
column5: 000 apps – we are not able to action on these at once or together in a consistent way as we are constrained in time by the appeals capacity.

column1: The hypothesis is that there are low hanging fruit wins that can be addressed in the current appeals process to unlock appeals bandwidth in the short term. There is also an opportunity to understand what other pinpoints that are can be addressed (in the longer term) with engineering (tooling) support. We are asking for a UXR resource that can work alongside the Appeals team to identify these pinpoints and suggest opportunities. This is critical for short term velocity and impact – there is no resource in the Appeals team available for this work (they are all responding to and managing appeals).
• Map out the user flow of the main uses cases / problems that bring app developers to appeal (related to an SDK issue). Start from the Play developer console experience
• Root cause study of the issues (appeals are the symptoms). This includes detailed analysis upstream

o How to provide sufficient information to developers upon enforcement so that developer can self-fix the issues without coming to appeals (eg. what information is missing for dev to self-fix issues?)
o How to increase the awareness of SDK violations so that developers are aware that they are required to make fixes while they are not intentionally violating policies
o How to effectively warn developers so that they fix issues in advance to the enforcement
o How to educate developers on technical details (eg. need to roll out updated APK at 100% to deactivate non-compliant APK)

column2: identify the friction areas and the business impact of these friction areas (# staff involved
column3: time to Google and to the app developer

column1: • Size (relatively) and prioritize amongst these use cases
• Identify opportunities / potential solutions for the main friction points
• Capture opportunities for other appeals workflows
After some changes have been implemented
column2: do continuous analysis of the impact and additional areas for improvements

column1: • Compare the original user flow to the new user flow across main use cases
• Do a comparison study of metrics
• Identify additional opportunities for improvement or adjustment
*Note that if there is bandwidth available
column2: we will also ask UXR to focus on opportunities on handling partner apps within this flow (as a specific use case).
